[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The characteristics of the metaprogramming metalanguages above are common to all Schorre metacompilers and those derived from them.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] META I was a hand compiled metacompiler used to compile META II.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Little else is known of META I except that the initial compilation of META II produced nearly identical code to that of the hand coded META I compiler.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Each rule consists optionally of tests, operators, and output productions.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] A rule attempts to match some part of the input program source character stream returning success or failure.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] On success the input is advanced over matched characters.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Output productions produced a form of assembly code directly from a syntax rule.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] META III is an evolution of META II, developed by Frederik W Schneider and Glen D Johnson.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Matched identifiers, strings, digits, etc are pushed into a operand stack, and new operators are added to manipulate it as needed.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] An explicit FIFO queue, when used together with the operand stack, enables intricate manipulations of the operands, such as conversion from depth-first to breath-first.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] There is a explicit symbol table, together with operators to edit and query it.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Finally, there is a concept of register tracking indented to facilitate generation of optimal register manipulation sequences.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] TREE-META introduced tree building operators **:**<*node_name*> and **[**<*number*>**]** moving the output production transforms to unparsed rules.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The tree building operators were used in the grammar rules directly transforming the input into an abstract syntax tree.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Unparse rules are also test functions that matched tree patterns.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Unparse rules are called from a grammar rule when an abstract syntax tree is to be transformed into output code.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The building of an abstract syntax tree and unparse rules allowed local optimizations to be performed by analyzing the parse tree.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Moving of output productions to the unparse rules made a clear separation of grammar analysis and code production.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] This made the programming easier to read and understand.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] In 1968–1970, Erwin Book, Dewey Val Schorre, and Steven J.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] CWIC is a compiler development system composed of three special-purpose, domain specific, languages, each intended to permit the description of certain aspects of translation in a straight forward manner.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The syntax language is used to describe the recognition of source text and the construction from it to an intermediate tree structure.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The generator language is used to describe the transformation of the tree into appropriate object language.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The syntax language follows Dewey Val Schorre's previous line of metacompilers.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] It most resembles TREE-META having tree building operators in the syntax language.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The unparse rules of TREE-META are extended to work with the object based generator language based on LISP 2.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] Generators Language had semantics similar to Lisp.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The parse tree was thought of as a recursive list.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The code to process a given tree included the features of a general purpose programming language, plus a form: <stuff>, which would emit (stuff) onto the output file.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] A generator call may be used in the unparse_rule.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] The generator is passed the element of unparse_rule pattern in which it is placed and its return values are listed in ().
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] That is, if the parse tree looks like (ADD[<something1>,<something2>]), expr_gen(x) would be called with <something1> and return x.
