[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] "A metacompiler assists the task of compiler-building by automating its non creative aspects, those aspects that are the same regardless of the language which the produced compiler is to translate.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/compiler-compiler] This makes possible the design of languages which are appropriate to the specification of a particular problem.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] An automated incremental computing tool is a specialised program analysis tool for optimization.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] Some approaches to incremental computing are specialized, while others are general purpose.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] Specialized approaches require the programmer to explicitly specify the algorithms and data structures that will be used to preserve unchanged sub-calculations.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] General-purpose approaches, on the other hand, use language, compiler, or algorithmic techniques to give incremental behavior to otherwise non-incremental programs.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] Given a computation $C=f(x_{1},x_{2},\dots x_{n})$ and a potential change $x_{j}:=\Delta _{x_{j}}$ , we can insert code before the change occurs (the pre-derivative) and after the change (the post-derivative) to update the value of C faster than rerunning f .
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] Paige has written down a list of rules for formal differentiation of programs in SUBSETL.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] In database systems such as DBToaster, views are defined with relational algebra.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] *Incremental view maintenance* statically analyzes relational algebra to create update rules that quickly maintain the view in the presence of small updates, such as insertion of a row.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] Incremental computation can be achieved by building a dependency graph of all the data elements that may need to be recalculated, and their dependencies.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] The elements that need to be updated when a single element changes are given by the transitive closure of the dependency relation of the graph.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] In other words, if there is a path from the changed element to another element, the latter may be updated (depending on whether the change eventually reaches the element).
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] The dependency graph may need to be updated as dependencies change, or as elements are added to, or removed from, the system.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] It is used internally by the implementation, and does not typically need to be displayed to the user.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] Partial evaluation can be combined with other incremental computing techniques.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] With cycles in the dependency graph, a single pass through the graph may not be sufficient to reach a fixed point.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/incremental-computing] In some cases, complete re-evaluation of a system is semantically equivalent to incremental evaluation, and may be more efficient in practice if not in theory.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A **parse tree** or **parsing tree** (also known as a **derivation tree** or **concrete syntax tree**) is an ordered, rooted tree that represents the syntactic structure of a string according to some context-free grammar.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The term *parse tree* itself is used primarily in computational linguistics; in theoretical syntax, the term *syntax tree* is more common.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Concrete syntax trees reflect the syntax of the input language, making them distinct from the abstract syntax trees used in computer programming.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Unlike Reed-Kellogg sentence diagrams used for teaching grammar, parse trees do not use distinct symbol shapes for different types of constituents.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Parse trees are usually constructed based on either the constituency relation of constituency grammars (phrase structure grammars) or the dependency relation of dependency grammars.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Parse trees may be generated for sentences in natural languages (see natural language processing), as well as during processing of computer languages, such as programming languages.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A related concept is that of **phrase marker** or **P-marker**, as used in transformational generative grammar.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A phrase marker is a linguistic expression marked as to its phrase structure.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] This may be presented in the form of a tree, or as a bracketed expression.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Phrase markers are generated by applying phrase structure rules, and themselves are subject to further transformational rules.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A set of possible parse trees for a syntactically ambiguous sentence is called a "parse forest".
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A form of parse tree was in use as early as 1879 in Gottlob Frege's *Begriffsschrift* book.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A parse tree is made up of nodes and branches.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] In the picture the parse tree is the entire structure, starting from S and ending in each of the leaf nodes (John, ball, the, hit).
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] In a parse tree, each node is either a *root* node, a *branch* node, or a *leaf* node.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] In the above example, S is a root node, NP and VP are branch nodes, while John, ball, the, and hit are all leaf nodes.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Nodes can also be referred to as parent nodes and child nodes.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A *parent* node is one which has at least one other node linked by a branch under it.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] In the example, S is a parent of both NP and VP.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A *child* node is one which has at least one node directly above it to which it is linked by a branch of the tree.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Again from our example, hit is a child node of V.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A **nonterminal function** is a function (node) which is either a root or a branch in that tree whereas a **terminal function** is a function (node) in a parse tree which is a leaf.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] For binary trees (where each parent node has two immediate child nodes), the number of possible parse trees for a sentence with *n* words is given by the Catalan number $C_{n}$ .
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The constituency-based parse trees of constituency grammars (phrase structure grammars) distinguish between terminal and non-terminal nodes.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The interior nodes are labeled by non-terminal categories of the grammar, while the leaf nodes are labeled by terminal categories.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The parse tree is the entire structure, starting from S and ending in each of the leaf nodes (*John*, *hit*, *the*, *ball*).
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Each node in the tree is either a *root* node, a *branch* node, or a *leaf* node.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A root node is a node that does not have any branches on top of it.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Within a sentence, there is only ever one root node.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A branch node is a parent node that connects to two or more child nodes.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A leaf node, however, is a terminal node that does not dominate other nodes in the tree.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] S is the root node, NP and VP are branch nodes, and *John* (N), *hit* (V), *the* (D), and *ball* (N) are all leaf nodes.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The leaves are the lexical tokens of the sentence.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A parent node is one that has at least one other node linked by a branch under it.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] In the example, S is a parent of both N and VP.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A child node is one that has at least one node directly above it to which it is linked by a branch of a tree.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] From the example, *hit* is a child node of V.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The terms *mother* and *daughter* are also sometimes used for this relationship.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The dependency-based parse trees of dependency grammars see all nodes as terminal, which means they do not acknowledge the distinction between terminal and non-terminal categories.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] They are simpler on average than constituency-based parse trees because they contain fewer nodes.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] This parse tree lacks the phrasal categories (S, VP, and NP) seen in the constituency-based counterpart above.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Like the constituency-based tree, constituent structure is acknowledged.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Any complete sub-tree of the tree is a constituent.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Thus this dependency-based parse tree acknowledges the subject noun *John* and the object noun phrase *the ball* as constituents just like the constituency-based parse tree does.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] The constituency vs. dependency distinction is far-reaching.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Whether the additional syntactic structure associated with constituency-based parse trees is necessary or beneficial is a matter of debate.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Phrase markers, or P-markers, were introduced in early transformational generative grammar, as developed by Noam Chomsky and others.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] A phrase marker representing the deep structure of a sentence is generated by applying phrase structure rules.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Then, this application may undergo further transformations.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] Phrase markers may be presented in the form of trees (as in the above section on constituency-based parse trees), but are often given instead in the form of "bracketed expressions", which occupy less space in the memory.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/parse-tree] As with trees, the precise construction of such expressions and the amount of detail shown can depend on the theory being applied and on the points that the query author wishes to illustrate.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter-parser-generator] Text editors which have official integrations with Tree-sitter include GNU Emacs, Neovim, Lapce, Zed, Helix, and Atom.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter-parser-generator] Language bindings allow it to be used from programming languages including Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript (with Node.js and WASM), Kotlin, Lua, OCaml, Perl, Python, Ruby, Rust, Swift, and Zig.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter-parser-generator] Tree-sitter parsers have been written for these languages and many others.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter-parser-generator] GitHub uses Tree-sitter to support in-browser symbolic code navigation in Git repositories.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter-parser-generator] Tree-sitter uses a GLR parser, a type of LR parser.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter-parser-generator] Tree-sitter was originally developed by GitHub for use in the Atom text editor, where it was first released in 2018.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter] Tree-sitter is a parser generator tool and an incremental parsing library.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter] It can build a concrete syntax tree for a source file and efficiently update the syntax tree as the source file is edited.
[src:tree-sitter-parsing/tree-sitter] A list of known parsers can be found in the wiki.
